# .leakguard — buyer-name / cycle-specific leak-guard patterns (gitignored).
#
# `make pre-push-check` reads this file (one regex per line) and greps every
# diff commit between origin/main and HEAD for matches. Any match BLOCKS the
# push so buyer-specific framing doesn't leak into committed history.
#
# To activate:
#   1. Copy this file to .leakguard:    cp .leakguard.example .leakguard
#   2. Edit .leakguard and replace the EXAMPLE entries below with the actual
#      tokens you want to scan for (buyer / company / contact / domain names,
#      product code names, internal program references, recipient email).
#   3. Re-run `make pre-push-check` to confirm "clean".
#
# Format:
#   - One regex per line (extended POSIX, used by `grep -iE`)
#   - Lines starting with # are comments and ignored
#   - Blank lines ignored
#   - Case-insensitive (driven by grep -i in the Makefile target)
#
# Why this is gitignored (CLAUDE.md § 6):
#   .leakguard contains buyer-specific tokens — committing it would leak the
#   very names it's supposed to scan for. The .example template is committed
#   to make first-fork setup discoverable; .leakguard itself never enters
#   version control.
#
# ─── EXAMPLES (replace before activating) ────────────────────────────────
#
# # Buyer/recipient names (English + native script if applicable):
# acme-corp
# AcmeCorp
# 株式会社エースミ
#
# # Recipient contacts:
# john\.doe@acme\.com
# Jane Doe
#
# # Product / program codes:
# project-zephyr
# AC-2026-Q2
#
# # Cycle-specific document filenames (avoid leaking via path quotes):
# acme-corp_steps\.md
EXAMPLE_BUYER_NAME
example\.contact@example\.com
